{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524654"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14021"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14021"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.15,0.09,0.34,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115904"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6670"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3731"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49537"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115904"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old youth presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless swelling in the left side of his neck. He is otherwise well and has no other symptoms. His mother and maternal grandmother had \u0027thyroid problems\u0027. He returned from a six-week trip to India one month ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 64/min, blood pressure 108/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The only abnormality found on general examination is a well-defined, soft neck swelling (Image). The skin moves freely over the swelling, but the lump itself does not move, either on palpation or when the patient swallows.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipoma","Thyroid nodule","Sebaceous cyst","Hodgkin lymphoma","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a young man with a painless neck swelling, which is most likely an enlarged lymph node. A smooth-surfaced swelling is visible arising out of the left supraclavicular fossa. The most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EHodgkin lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Hodgkin lymphoma typically presents with painless lymphadenopathy, often in the cervical or supraclavicular region. The patient\u0027s age (adolescent to young adult) is also characteristic of one of the peak incidence periods for Hodgkin lymphoma. The absence of B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss) does not rule out the diagnosis, as these are often absent in early-stage disease. Whilst palpable lymph nodes in Hodgkin lymphoma are characteristically described as being \u0027rubbery,\u0027 this is not always the case and they can be soft.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential diagnosis, especially given the patient\u0027s recent travel to India, where TB is endemic. However, tuberculous lymphadenitis is often tender and may be associated with constitutional symptoms, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid nodule\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely in this case. While there is a family history of thyroid problems, the location (side of the neck rather than midline) and the fact that the lump does not move with swallowing make a thyroid nodule less probable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign tumors of adipose tissue. They are typically soft, mobile, and painless. However, they are uncommon in the neck region and are usually more mobile than the lump described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esebaceous cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign cyst of the skin. While they can occur on the neck, they are typically smaller, more superficial, and associated with a visible punctum. The description of a well-defined, soft swelling that doesn\u0027t move is not typical of a sebaceous cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo confirm the diagnosis, further investigations would be necessary. An ultrasound and fine needle aspiration biopsy would be helpful to characterise the lesion, but the gold standard for diagnosing Hodgkin lymphoma is an excisional biopsy of the affected lymph node.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hodgkin lymphoma typically presents with painless lymphadenopathy, often in the neck or supraclavicular region.","B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss) are not always present in early-stage Hodgkin lymphoma.","Excisional biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosing Hodgkin lymphoma."],"references":["Brice P, de Kerviler E, Friedberg J. Classical Hodgkin lymphoma. Lancet 2021; 398:1518-27."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14021"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20934"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20934"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hJl1eh7E6sOORXDFx5zrTNK6NauTHc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hJl1eh7E6sOORXDFx5zrTNK6NauTHc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T08:20:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T08:20:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6670"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115904"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","